(1807, 50, '3. Which of these keywords is used to refer to member of base class from a subclass?', ' upper', ' super', ' this', ' none of the mentioned', ' b', 'Explanation: Whenever a subclass needs to refer to its immediate superclass, it can do so by use of the keyword super.'),
(1808, 50, '4. Which of these method of String class can be used to test to strings for equality?', ' isequal()', ' isequals()', ' equal()', ' equals()', ' d', ''),
(1809, 50, '5. Which of the following statements are incorrect?', ' String is a class', ' Strings in java are mutable', ' Every string is an object of class String', ' Java defines a peer class of String, called StringBuffer, which allows string to be altered', ' b', 'Explanation: Strings in Java are immutable that is they can not be modified.'),
(1810, 50, '1. Which of these is the method which is executed first before execution of any other thing takes place in a program?', ' main method', ' finalize method', ' static method', ' private method', ' c', 'Explanation: If a static method is present in the program then it will be executed first, then main will be executed.'),
(1811, 50, '2. What is the process of defining more than one method in a class differentiated by parameters?', ' Function overriding', ' Function overloading', ' Function doubling', ' None of the mentioned', ' b', 'Explanation: Function overloading is a process of defining more than one method in a class with same name differentiated by function signature i:e return type or parameters type and number. Example – int volume(int length, int width) & int volume(int length , int width , int height) can be used to calculate volume.'),
(1812, 50, '3. Which of these can be used to differentiate two or more methods having the same name?', ' Parameters data type', ' Number of parameters', ' Return type of method', ' All of the mentioned', ' d', 'Explanation: None.'),
(1813, 50, '4. Which of these data type can be used for a method having a return statement in it?', ' void', ' int', ' float', ' both int and float', ' d', 'Explanation: None.'),
